After seeing @trincot&#39;s link for `GeeksForGeeks` I updated my answer. There are also other constraints in terms of maximum N.
The only way I could think of doing this was to use the array values to index other values and bump each targeted value by the length of the array (this pushes those indexed values beyond the range of `0 to N-1`).

Any value which equals or exceeds twice the array length is a duplicate.

The problem was then how do continue using the array values to further index the array without throwing an `ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException`. So I used the remainder function with a modulus of the array length.

```
int[] arr = {
        13,9,25,1,1,0,22,13,22,20,3,8,11,25,10,3,15,11,19,20,2,4,25,14,
        23,14
};
        
List&lt;Integer&gt; result = duplicates(arr);
System.out.println(result);
```
prints
```
[1, 3, 11, 13, 14, 20, 22, 25]
```
The method.
```
public static List&lt;Integer&gt; duplicates(int arr[]) {
    
    List&lt;Integer&gt; result = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
   
    for (int i = 0; i &lt; arr.length; i++) {
        // only need to sum twice (also prevents overflow)
        int idx = arr[i] % arr.length;
        if (arr[idx] &lt; 2 * arr.length) {
            arr[idx] += arr.length;
        }
    }
    
    for (int i = 0; i &lt; arr.length; i++) {
       if (arr[i] &gt;= 2*arr.length) {
           result.add(i);
       }
    }
    return result.isEmpty() ? List.of(-1) : result;
}
```
Note: Passing the array length is not necessary or useful.  However, it can be added back in if required.

