If you want to run multiple transactions in parallel you could consider this possible solution


First some sort of java objects to deal with the concurrency of the application.

        private final Set&lt;Integer&gt; accountsInUse = ConcurrentHashMap.newKeySet();
        private final Set&lt;Future&lt;TransactionResult&gt;&gt; transactions = ConcurrentHashMap.newKeySet();
        private final ReentrantReadWriteLock lock = new ReentrantReadWriteLock();
        private final ReentrantReadWriteLock.ReadLock reader = lock.readLock();
        private final ReentrantReadWriteLock.WriteLock writer = lock.writeLock();
    
        private final ExecutorService executor = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(5);
        private final Timer transactionChecker = new Timer();


accountsInUse is basically  to know what accounts are beign used at the moment.  Reentrant objects are to protect accountsInUse to be written or read when another thread is accessing it.

The executor is to run your transactions in separately and transactions is to know if they already finish or not.

Now you need a callable class to do your operations 

    static class TransactionThread implements Callable&lt;TransactionResult&gt; {

        Account acc1;
        Account acc2;
        double amount;

        TransactionThread(Account acc1, Account acc2, double amount) {
            this.acc1 = acc1;
            this.acc2 = acc2;
            this.amount = amount;
        }

        @Override
        public TransactionResult call() throws Exception {
            if (acc1.getBalance() &lt; amount) {
                throw new InvalidAmountException(&quot;Not enough money in sender account&quot;);
            }

            if (amount &lt; 0) {
                throw new InvalidAmountException(&quot;Amount must be positive&quot;);
            }
            Account[] accounts = orderAccounts(acc1, acc2);

            acc1.setLastTransaction(new Transaction(-amount, acc1, acc2));
            acc1.updateBalance(-amount);
            acc2.setLastTransaction(new Transaction(amount, acc1, acc2));
            acc2.updateBalance(amount);

            return new TransactionResult(&quot;SUCCESS&quot;, acc1.getID(), acc2.getID());
        }
    }
    record TransactionResult(String status, int acc1Id, int acc2Id) {
    }

 
Then you need to update the method to run your transactions 



    public void transfer(String acc1, String acc2, double amount) throws InvalidAmountException,
                AccountNotExists, AccountNotAvailable, SafeIllegalArgumentException {
            //controllare se amount sia corretto, altrimenti errore, se ne occupa ConnectionHandler con IOException()
            writer.lock();
            if (acc1.equals(acc2)) {
                writer.unlock();
                throw new SafeIllegalArgumentException(&quot;You can&#39;t transfer money to yourself&quot;);
            }
            //devo verificare che il conto non sia nella lista transfer_i;
            Account g1 = getAccount(acc1);
            Account g2 = getAccount(acc2);
            reader.lock();
        if(accountsInUse.contains(g1.getID()) || accountsInUse.contains(g2.getID())) {
            writer.unlock();
            throw new SafeIllegalArgumentException(&quot;Accounts in Use&quot;);
        }
        reader.unlock();
        writer.lock();
        accountsInUse.add(g1.getID());
        accountsInUse.add(g2.getID());
        //se gli account non esistono viene lanciata l&#39;eccezione AccountNotExists gestito dal getAccount():
        transactions.add(executor.submit(new TransactionThread(g1, g2, amount)));
        writer.unlock();
        }

Here you use the WriteLock and ReadLock to prevent other thread to write/read in your accsountsInUse Set while is not allowed.

Note that every thread you execute with the Executor return a Future, That object will tell you if the process is over or not.

So finally, you need something to check for the Future list of objects (transactions). A timer can help on this.

So in your constructor:

    public Bank() {
            accounts = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
            transfer_i = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
            TimerTask taskChecker = new TimerTask() {
                @Override
                public void run() {
                    reader.lock();
                    List&lt;Integer&gt; finishedTransactions = transactions.stream()
                            .filter(Future::isDone).map(f-&gt;{
                                try {
                                    return f.get();
                                } catch (InterruptedException | ExecutionException e) {
                                    throw new RuntimeException(e);
                                }
                            })
                            .flatMap(tr -&gt; Stream.of(tr.acc1Id(), tr.acc2Id()))
                            .toList();
                    accountsInUse.stream().filter(finishedTransactions::contains).toList().forEach(accountsInUse::remove);
                    reader.unlock();
                }
            };
            transactionChecker.schedule(taskChecker, 0, 1000);
        }


This is just a simple timer that will be checking for all finished transactions  and remove them from the accountsInUse Set if they are done..

There are lots of improvements that can be made here but I just did a quick sample on how you can handle this. Hope this helps.

