Is it really necessary to `lock.unlock()` in a `finally` block? The following is a common idiom
```java
try {
    lock.lock();
    // some code
} catch (Exception e) {
    // exception handling
} finally {
    lock.unlock();
}
```
however, here&#39;s what [the Java Language Specification](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se8/html/jls-17.html) has to say:

&gt; If execution of the body is ever completed, either normally **or abruptly** *[presumably, e.g. due to an exception]*, an **unlock action is automatically performed** on that same monitor.

Is it really necessary to put `lock.unlock()` in a `finally` block then? Or did I misunderstand the specification?

