First, in your configuration, you defined `generate-ddl: true`. This allows JPA to alter the database schema according to your entity definition. In case your database is already initialized, you turn it to false.

Second, you can use `@Temporal` to define the precision of your date/datetime/timestamp value in the database. When you have only the precision of the date, then you can use `@Temporal(TemporalType.DATE)` to define the precision for the database column. You could, for example, use the Java class with the corresponding precision.
```java
@Temporal(TemporalType.DATE)
private java.util.Date updatedAt;
```

